of an urban policy
was promulgated.

00:23:49.530 --> 00:23:53.220
It was worth noting that it
followed an accurate map."

00:23:56.240 --> 00:24:03.190
Turgot, he made the first
correct map of Paris.

00:24:03.190 --> 00:24:06.960
It was correct in the sense
that it was more accurate

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:14.610
than the typical perspective
view of cities up to that time.

00:24:14.610 --> 00:24:20.910
The Great Map of Rome
by Nolli was 1748.

00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:27.060
And Turgot did as best he could.

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:32.880
The great first
orthographic map of Paris

00:24:32.880 --> 00:24:40.200
was the work of a Burgundian
architect called Verniquet.

00:24:40.200 --> 00:24:50.270
Verniquet took
accurate measurements

00:24:50.270 --> 00:24:53.630
during the day in the
crowded Paris streets.

00:24:53.630 --> 00:24:57.110
His grand observations were
corrected by triangulation

00:24:57.110 --> 00:25:01.520
to determine the
elevations of the city.

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:06.290
In 1783, there's an
interesting connection

00:25:06.290 --> 00:25:11.210
between the availability of an
accurate map and the capacity

00:25:11.210 --> 00:25:14.300
to make a pronouncement
of urban policy.

00:25:18.260 --> 00:25:26.380
The streets are important
for the public welfare.

00:25:26.380 --> 00:25:29.950
They ought to be sufficiently
wide and free of any barriers

00:25:29.950 --> 00:25:35.920
to the free and easy passage
of vehicles and pedestrians.

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:39.650
They further asserted
that overly tall buildings

00:25:39.650 --> 00:25:45.040
were prejudicial to clean air
in a city as populous as Paris

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:49.600
as well as contrary to public
safety and prone to fire.

00:25:49.600 --> 00:26:01.650
Already, in 1793,
there was not only

00:26:01.650 --> 00:26:04.980
the ability to demarcate
space accurately

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:08.550
because of an accurate
map, but the capacity

00:26:08.550 --> 00:26:11.820
to put into place
regulations which

00:26:11.820 --> 00:26:15.180
decided what the
dimensions of a street

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:20.160
were and also of the
ruling, which has lasted

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:23.160
in central Paris
ever since, and that

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:25.980
is not to allow tall buildings.

00:26:34.770 --> 00:26:38.970
Whilst the spatial
idea of having

00:26:38.970 --> 00:26:46.930
as direct a distance between
two monumental points

00:26:46.930 --> 00:26:48.960
was an idea which
had been around

00:26:48.960 --> 00:26:53.100
in French landscape
for a long time,

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:55.530
there was nobody, really,
who could articulate

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:56.715
that idea in practice.

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:04.310
The street system was
not only for play.

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:07.340
It was for rapid movement.

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:11.120
Denied by the building
of barricades,

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:14.690
the street system
was also a sequence

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:21.780
of connectivity between
various aspects of the city.

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:24.860
Already, early on,
the French King

00:27:24.860 --> 00:27:28.430
decided that the university
would be on the Left Bank

00:27:28.430 --> 00:27:31.620
and commerce would
be on the Right Bank.

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:40.400
But instead of developing
these as the sole elements

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:45.080
of the space, a system of
avenues which connected

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:50.360
the important points, often
monuments, reticulated and made

00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:56.450
a multidimensional space,
in this case, a box

00:27:56.450 --> 00:28:03.690
base of limited height but
a compressed space, now

00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:09.860
of two million people, all
articulated by the rulings

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:12.620
about streets.

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:22.360
Haussmann, who became
prefect in 1851,

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:30.740
was really responsible for
being the first urban manager

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:35.990
in any city in
relatively recent times.

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:38.540
What he did was
take an idea which

00:28:38.540 --> 00:28:43.790
was in the DNA of the French
Parisian system of streets

00:28:43.790 --> 00:28:46.160
and make it possible.

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:51.560
Paris was an unruly
medieval city.

00:28:51.560 --> 00:28:56.000
It was-- you read
Stendhal, he talks

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:00.630
about the mud in the streets
and the filth in the streets.

00:29:00.630 --> 00:29:04.040
It was no different from
most cities at that time.

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:12.290
And it also was the
site of cholera.

00:29:12.290 --> 00:29:17.420
There were great cholera
epidemics in 1839 and in 1842.

00:29:17.420 --> 00:29:21.810
There were workers
riots regularly

00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:25.670
in 1830s, the 1840s,
this following

00:29:25.670 --> 00:29:33.080
that Great Revolution of 1789.

00:29:33.080 --> 00:29:37.320
Haussmann arrived
after the failure

00:29:37.320 --> 00:29:42.110
of the last-- second-last
king to maintain his position,

00:29:42.110 --> 00:29:45.320
and he was replaced
by Louis Napoleon.

00:29:45.320 --> 00:29:50.420
Louis Napoleon
had been in exile.

00:29:50.420 --> 00:29:57.380
And there are stories of
him being in Durgin-Park,

00:29:57.380 --> 00:30:00.560
in the restaurant
in Boston, talking

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:03.170
about this great new city
that he was going to build

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:06.080
when he went back to Paris.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:08.560
He had watched Regent
Street in London

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:11.332
and, with great
admiration for the--

00:30:11.332 --> 00:30:14.870
what built Regent
Street in London.

00:30:14.870 --> 00:30:19.790
The compact included
permission by the Parliament,

00:30:19.790 --> 00:30:23.270
a million pounds of
money from the bank,

00:30:23.270 --> 00:30:32.650
and the right to
purchase property

00:30:32.650 --> 00:30:35.860
in order that the property
may be transformed according

00:30:35.860 --> 00:30:36.880
to a street system.

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:47.550
Louis Napoleon was
obsessed with this idea

00:30:47.550 --> 00:30:50.910
that he could rebuild Paris.

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:55.890
He happens to be the last
king in the history of Paris.

00:30:55.890 --> 00:31:01.800
He made a bad decision to
start a war with the Prussians,

00:31:01.800 --> 00:31:13.590
and Paris was bombarded and
the court moved to Versailles

00:31:13.590 --> 00:31:18.090
and a republic was
established after the war.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:23.040
So Haussmann's 20
years are 20 years

00:31:23.040 --> 00:31:32.010
at the end of 900 years
of royal regime in Paris.

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:38.610
You cannot account for a similar
set of circumstances in London

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:42.960
or in Vienna or in Berlin or any
of the great European cities.

00:31:47.810 --> 00:31:54.760
Haussmann was a maniac
for a number of things.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:58.150
Spatially, I don't know
about his personal life here.

00:31:58.150 --> 00:32:00.090
That's another story altogether.

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:06.800
He wanted absolute control.

00:32:06.800 --> 00:32:09.520
He says to the Emperor--

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:13.480
when they have the first meeting
of the town planning commission

00:32:13.480 --> 00:32:15.640
and there are lots of
speeches and everybody's

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:17.290
sitting around--

00:32:17.290 --> 00:32:19.330
he talks to the Emperor
after the meeting

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:22.420
and says, "What a waste of time.

00:32:22.420 --> 00:32:25.630
All these people like big
speeches, and nothing happened.

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:26.980
We don't get any work done."

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:29.590
The Emperor says, "Well,
how big does the commission

00:32:29.590 --> 00:32:30.670
have to be?"

00:32:30.670 --> 00:32:33.400
He says, "Well, the Emperor,
you would have to be there

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:37.120
and I have to be there, and I
can't think of anybody else."

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:40.330
The Emperor says, "Sounds
like a good plan to me."

00:32:40.330 --> 00:32:45.820
So the commission becomes one
man, the Prefect of the Seine.

00:32:45.820 --> 00:32:49.090
Rambuteau, the Prefect
of the Seine before him--

00:32:49.090 --> 00:32:52.990
there were a number of others,
Berger and Persigny and so on--

00:32:52.990 --> 00:32:59.980
but Rambuteau tried to
extend the East-West access

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:03.835
to the Bastille, as Napoleon
tried to do, but failed.

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:13.270
He proposed the street which
has his name, the Rue Rambuteau,

00:33:13.270 --> 00:33:16.840
but could only afford
to build it out

00:33:16.840 --> 00:33:20.260
of the budget of the city.

00:33:20.260 --> 00:33:27.700
He could build one mile, and
he was allowed to make it.

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:31.180
He only asked for
13 meters width.

00:33:31.180 --> 00:33:33.590
He was allowed 20 meters.

00:33:33.590 --> 00:33:37.210
But the story of Rambuteau is
the story of the fact that you

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:42.220
cannot do a major reconstruction
of a city out of the capital

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:44.800
budget of the city.

00:33:44.800 --> 00:33:49.950
What the greatest
invention of Haussmann,

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:54.270
it was not easy arrangement,
but economists like Saint-Simon

00:33:54.270 --> 00:34:02.640
constructed the idea that if you
improved an asset, its worth,

00:34:02.640 --> 00:34:05.820
no matter how much you
invest in the improvement,

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:09.285
its worth in the end is going
to pay it back many times.

00:34:11.830 --> 00:34:15.310
It's called deficit
spending, today.

00:34:15.310 --> 00:34:17.620
And Haussmann
understood that in order

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:25.630
to rebuild Paris from being a
medieval slum to a modern city,

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:29.020
you needed to
develop more capital

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:33.159
than the ordinary taxation
system in the city can do.

00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:45.730
So he took the money from the
octroi system, borrowed money.

00:34:45.730 --> 00:34:49.630
He expropriated land.

00:34:49.630 --> 00:34:56.219
In 1783-- no.

00:34:56.219 --> 00:35:02.790
Slowly, in the 18th century, the
control of Paris by the kings

00:35:02.790 --> 00:35:04.440
diminished.

00:35:04.440 --> 00:35:07.080
And when the rule-- after
the Revolution, of course,

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:10.615
there were no kings until Louis
Philippe and Louis Napoleon.

00:35:13.800 --> 00:35:21.480
The notion that you could move
people out of their domains,

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:26.370
rebuild the premises in
which they lived, and not

00:35:26.370 --> 00:35:31.810
care for them through
replacement accommodation

00:35:31.810 --> 00:35:35.340
and so on, took hold
under Haussmann.

00:35:35.340 --> 00:35:38.730
Haussmann, in 20
years, rebuilt Paris

00:35:38.730 --> 00:35:44.430
in ways which were part of
the DNA street system of Paris

00:35:44.430 --> 00:35:50.805
and made possible, in modern
times, by deficit spending.

00:35:53.830 --> 00:35:56.820
The loans which
Haussmann accumulated

00:35:56.820 --> 00:36:03.030
in the 20 years where
only repaid in 1929,

00:36:03.030 --> 00:36:09.030
but Paris was an immensely
more valuable city in 1929

00:36:09.030 --> 00:36:14.110
than it was in 1850.

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:20.520
So we have the introduction into
the urban system of a business

00:36:20.520 --> 00:36:25.020
model, of a management model.

00:36:25.020 --> 00:36:28.290
Haussmann had his
own predilections.

00:36:28.290 --> 00:36:30.930
He did not believe that
individual buildings

00:36:30.930 --> 00:36:32.190
were important.

00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:35.590
He believed that the systems
of building were important.

00:36:35.590 --> 00:36:39.030
He hated the idiosyncrasy.

00:36:39.030 --> 00:36:42.150
All the buildings had
to be the same height.

00:36:42.150 --> 00:36:46.200
There's an image
in what I gave you.

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:52.590
There's a photograph
of a street in Paris

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:59.250
where he forces the
property on the left

00:36:59.250 --> 00:37:03.540
to shift its turret
to the street in order

00:37:03.540 --> 00:37:06.572
that it balance a building
on the opposite side

00:37:06.572 --> 00:37:07.155
of the street.

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:12.780
What else?

00:37:12.780 --> 00:37:16.500
This is an enormously
long story,

00:37:16.500 --> 00:37:19.270
but I'm giving you
the bounds of it.

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:22.650
If you're interested,
there's good literature

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:25.050
on the history of
Paris and certainly

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:36.590
the period of 1850 to 1870.

00:37:36.590 --> 00:37:42.330
What else can I say before
we look at some images?

00:37:42.330 --> 00:37:45.200
This is about as bare
a description of Paris

00:37:45.200 --> 00:37:48.810
as I can imagine.

00:37:48.810 --> 00:37:53.000
But the extraordinary
capacity for the street system

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:58.640
to be the major articulator
of movement, of war,

00:37:58.640 --> 00:38:10.200
of play, of distribution,
of psychogeography,

00:38:10.200 --> 00:38:14.160
Haussmann felt that if
you look down an avenue,

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:17.640
you had to have a closed vista.

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:22.110
You had to be led to something
which was an important place.

00:38:22.110 --> 00:38:28.760
In Washington, which has a
kind of Parisian kind of plan,

00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:33.620
the intersections of
the diagonal avenues,

00:38:33.620 --> 00:38:36.335
where they meet each
other, produce nothing.

00:38:38.980 --> 00:38:42.550
In Paris, there's always an
important square or monument.

00:38:42.550 --> 00:38:51.060
When Haussmann decides that we--
that the city needs an opera,

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:55.920
he builds the Rue de Opera
and then the opera itself.

00:38:55.920 --> 00:39:00.690
The opera, it has an
extraordinary interior.

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:05.430
Adding to the complexity of the
spatial relationship of access

00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:07.020
to the opera--

00:39:07.020 --> 00:39:10.530
the facade of the opera is
a monument standing freely

00:39:10.530 --> 00:39:11.640
in space--

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:18.090
and then the entrance and
interior, a fantastic interior,

00:39:18.090 --> 00:39:21.050
as well.

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:25.340
What you have in this
Haussmannian system

00:39:25.340 --> 00:39:32.690
is this state set of
multifunctional connectors

00:39:32.690 --> 00:39:36.200
tying decentralized
aspects of it.

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:38.902
There's no center to Paris.

00:39:38.902 --> 00:39:39.860
There are many centers.

00:39:45.350 --> 00:39:50.920
You have, as you'll see
in some of the slides,

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:55.610
passages connecting
with covered roofs

00:39:55.610 --> 00:39:57.620
in between the boulevards.

00:40:03.520 --> 00:40:09.380
You have an articulate and
very elementary system based,

00:40:09.380 --> 00:40:14.030
as I say, on of DNA of Paris
since the 15th century.

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:19.550
Why the French
articulated their space

00:40:19.550 --> 00:40:24.080
around the idea of minimizing
distance between points

00:40:24.080 --> 00:40:28.370
and being articulate about that
distance and the experience

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:33.050
of that distance is
still, to me, unclear.

00:40:33.050 --> 00:40:38.820
But it's absolutely different
from the case of London,

00:40:38.820 --> 00:40:41.340
where we have one
street, Regent Street,

00:40:41.340 --> 00:40:46.290
artifacted in a similar pathway.

00:40:46.290 --> 00:40:49.080
As Haussmann did it,
the scale of a city.

00:40:52.800 --> 00:40:57.670
I need to see if there's
anything else I should say.

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:01.360
Any questions?

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:03.910
STUDENT: If I understood
what you said earlier,

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:09.730
it was that the idea of a street
or a path connecting monuments

00:41:09.730 --> 00:41:13.420
is like an older
idea than Haussmann.

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:15.550
If I understood you
correctly, like, where

00:41:15.550 --> 00:41:18.280
did that originate from, like
in Paris or in French culture?

00:41:18.280 --> 00:41:19.840
JULIAN BEINART:
Well, I don't know.

00:41:19.840 --> 00:41:21.700
As you'll see, in
the second slide I

00:41:21.700 --> 00:41:28.330
will show you of an image of
streets in the 15th century--

00:41:28.330 --> 00:41:29.360
oh, it's later.

00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:32.590
It's probably 17th
century Paris.

00:41:32.590 --> 00:41:34.870
You will see
diagonal road systems

00:41:34.870 --> 00:41:38.260
in these rural
areas around Paris

00:41:38.260 --> 00:41:41.740
as well as in some
in Paris itself.

00:41:41.740 --> 00:41:44.980
When I talk about
the DNA of a city,

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:48.680
I don't know exactly
what I'm saying.

00:41:48.680 --> 00:41:52.960
It's a biological
explanation, assuming

00:41:52.960 --> 00:41:57.700
that there are repetitive
elements, significant elements

00:41:57.700 --> 00:42:00.340
in a culture, which repeat.

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:03.850
Often, we don't quite know why.

00:42:03.850 --> 00:42:06.100
I often think that the
French are probably

00:42:06.100 --> 00:42:09.430
more direct than anybody
else philosophically

00:42:09.430 --> 00:42:13.210
and probably decided,
like Bismarck did,

00:42:13.210 --> 00:42:18.550
that the way to fight a war
is to go in a straight line

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:21.460
because you'll find nobody
else on the straight line.

00:42:21.460 --> 00:42:26.200
Everybody else is fussing
around all over the place.

00:42:26.200 --> 00:42:31.600
It's the direct
avenue to accomplish

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:35.970
the friction of distance.

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:39.810
I can't-- I wish
I could answer it.

00:42:39.810 --> 00:42:42.810
I'm sure a French, if we
had a French scholar here

00:42:42.810 --> 00:42:47.220
or a French historian,
there may be a--

00:42:47.220 --> 00:42:54.060
I've often looked for an
answer, but I haven't found it.

00:42:54.060 --> 00:42:58.980
It's interesting to
raise that question

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:02.010
because, now, two
million people are living

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:07.330
in this precious construction,
and six million people are

00:43:07.330 --> 00:43:11.950
living in bungalows, in public
housing, because public housing

00:43:11.950 --> 00:43:15.790
was not asserted as an
element to be incorporated

00:43:15.790 --> 00:43:17.830
into the Haussmannian puzzle.

00:43:20.810 --> 00:43:25.280
The city now has
this empty sprawl,

00:43:25.280 --> 00:43:27.890
which everybody dislikes.

00:43:27.890 --> 00:43:34.540
And Sarkozy says, I need
to do something about it.

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:43.720
I don't know if you
followed this competition.

00:43:43.720 --> 00:43:44.730
Did you?

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:46.205
Did you see the results?

00:43:46.205 --> 00:43:48.372
STUDENT: I remember seeing
some of these renderings,

00:43:48.372 --> 00:43:49.316
but I don't know.

00:43:49.316 --> 00:43:50.566
I don't know what's going to--

00:43:50.566 --> 00:43:53.590
JULIAN BEINART:
Oh, it was, I'm--

00:43:53.590 --> 00:43:57.680
I don't know if there's a book
of the entrants now available,

00:43:57.680 --> 00:44:01.870
but it was subject to a lot
of publicity at the time.

00:44:01.870 --> 00:44:04.690
And the images I've
just gathered here

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:08.530
are taken from some of
the publicity at the time.

00:44:15.050 --> 00:44:17.930
A number of things that one
wants to say about this.

00:44:23.630 --> 00:44:32.760
Everybody acknowledges
that the way to enlarge--

00:44:32.760 --> 00:44:36.610
not to enlarge,
to fill the space,

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:39.910
empty space around
the concentrated city,

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:42.020
is not to expand
the city itself.

