in the competition which

00:44:52.020 --> 00:44:57.840
use streets, avenues,
diagonalized systems

00:44:57.840 --> 00:45:00.600
as an extension of
the Haussmannian grid.

00:45:12.330 --> 00:45:27.550
There are many attempts to
do strong constructions,

00:45:27.550 --> 00:45:30.730
strong constructions
meaning constructions

00:45:30.730 --> 00:45:34.620
which have a strong
physical spatial dimension.

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:52.270
For instance, Grumbach proposes
that Paris will extend itself

00:45:52.270 --> 00:45:55.870
westward along with the Seine
to accommodate something

00:45:55.870 --> 00:46:00.430
like 16 million people,
arguing that every great city

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:02.470
in the world is a
port city and Paris

00:46:02.470 --> 00:46:04.000
should become a port city.

00:46:08.356 --> 00:46:11.926
A linear city of 16 miles--

00:46:11.926 --> 00:46:15.875
or 16 million people would take
about an hour by public transit

00:46:15.875 --> 00:46:20.030
or fast train from
Paris to Rouen.

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:24.735
And it's a strong idea.

00:46:27.500 --> 00:46:32.180
You can imagine a city
like this, following

00:46:32.180 --> 00:46:39.340
this pattern and developing
interesting relationships

00:46:39.340 --> 00:46:43.790
between public transportation
along the water

00:46:43.790 --> 00:46:45.380
and many aspects of it.

00:46:48.210 --> 00:46:52.620
What will stop it
from developing

00:46:52.620 --> 00:46:58.200
the same condition of sprawl
as now exists, I don't know.

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:01.350
He doesn't detail very
much about anything other

00:47:01.350 --> 00:47:05.250
than the concept itself.

00:47:05.250 --> 00:47:07.380
There are some
crazy propositions.

00:47:07.380 --> 00:47:10.890
The one is to take, just
close the Gare du Nord

00:47:10.890 --> 00:47:14.760
and shift the Gare do
Nord into the Banlieues

00:47:14.760 --> 00:47:18.510
and have it as the premier
railway station in Europe.

00:47:24.260 --> 00:47:26.900
Richard Rogers, the
British architect,

00:47:26.900 --> 00:47:29.120
has a modest proposal.

00:47:29.120 --> 00:47:32.510
He's really interested
in the the politics

00:47:32.510 --> 00:47:35.660
of all of the groups
in the Banlieues

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:38.710
and how they could
be brought together.

00:47:38.710 --> 00:47:43.480
He extends some of
the radial system,

00:47:43.480 --> 00:47:47.430
but covers them with green--

00:47:47.430 --> 00:47:50.430
remember that the
computation was called

00:47:50.430 --> 00:47:54.000
for post-Kyoto Resolution.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:58.770
Post-Kyoto means that the
ecological consequences

00:47:58.770 --> 00:48:03.440
of the plan were important.

00:48:03.440 --> 00:48:06.660
Jean Nouvel, for instance--

00:48:06.660 --> 00:48:17.010
many of the competitors proposed
to cover all the buildings

00:48:17.010 --> 00:48:22.530
with sun collectors, energy
collectors from the sun.

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:26.830
Jean Nouvel says,
all of the housing,

00:48:26.830 --> 00:48:32.010
public housing built
in the Banlieues

00:48:32.010 --> 00:48:34.200
are just bad buildings.

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:38.070
They just can't keep
them and convert them

00:48:38.070 --> 00:48:44.400
in as interesting and
dramatic and up-to-date

00:48:44.400 --> 00:48:47.700
fashion as possible.

00:48:47.700 --> 00:48:50.710
He says silly
things like, "Paris

00:48:50.710 --> 00:48:55.640
must become the great art
center of the world again."

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:58.650
He proposes something on
the Ile de Cité which I

00:48:58.650 --> 00:48:59.820
can't understand.

00:49:02.790 --> 00:49:09.360
There's almost a sense of
tiredness about the scheme,

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:12.900
as if there isn't
really a formula

00:49:12.900 --> 00:49:15.735
anymore for making urban space.

00:49:18.770 --> 00:49:25.670
Haussmann has really
terminated 900 years

00:49:25.670 --> 00:49:32.570
of French royal effort to build
walls, to build monuments.

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:43.400
Imagine having a monument in
the center of a city which

00:49:43.400 --> 00:49:49.710
was built by the first king
and then torn down and rebuilt

00:49:49.710 --> 00:49:52.080
by the second king and
then rebuilt and rebuilt

00:49:52.080 --> 00:49:55.800
and rebuilt and
rebuilt as the Paris--

00:49:55.800 --> 00:50:03.970
as a palace, ending
up with I.M. Pei doing

00:50:03.970 --> 00:50:07.960
a kind of central focal
point for it after it

00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:11.035
becomes a museum after a
thousand years of palace.

00:50:13.670 --> 00:50:15.560
It's the largest
museum in the world,

00:50:15.560 --> 00:50:22.460
I think, and certainly
probably the most significant.

00:50:22.460 --> 00:50:24.350
Yet it's on the River Seine.

00:50:24.350 --> 00:50:26.930
It blocks access to the river.

00:50:26.930 --> 00:50:32.390
It's a big block of
something or other.

00:50:32.390 --> 00:50:35.630
It's as permanent as
the city, and there's

00:50:35.630 --> 00:50:39.236
no moving it as many have.

00:50:39.236 --> 00:50:42.090
And there's, in
a class later on,

00:50:42.090 --> 00:50:46.340
we look at temporary
environments in cities.

00:50:46.340 --> 00:50:52.100
I will go through the various
French five French exhibitions

00:50:52.100 --> 00:50:53.400
in the center of Paris.

00:50:53.400 --> 00:51:01.070
1855, four years after the
Crystal Palace; 1868; 1879,

00:51:01.070 --> 00:51:04.820
I think; 1889; and 1900.

00:51:04.820 --> 00:51:07.115
1889, of course,
the Eiffel Tower.

00:51:10.220 --> 00:51:13.580
Jean Giraudoux, the
French playwright,

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:20.810
talks about the center of
Paris as being a stone site,

00:51:20.810 --> 00:51:27.440
a permanent, fixed,
[INAUDIBLE] set of operations,

00:51:27.440 --> 00:51:30.620
and these temporary
exhibitions are the sort

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:32.850
of way of animating them.

00:51:32.850 --> 00:51:36.570
It's like a circus coming
to small town once a year.

00:51:39.130 --> 00:51:41.200
It's an extraordinary
idea, that a city

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:45.730
could be fossilized in
some sort of way, gaining

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:48.190
in prestige, becoming
the greatest tourist

00:51:48.190 --> 00:51:51.280
city of the world.

00:51:51.280 --> 00:51:56.170
Why is Paris the greatest
tourist city of the world?

00:51:56.170 --> 00:51:58.900
What is there about
its spatial strategy

00:51:58.900 --> 00:52:06.600
that I've tried to spend
an hour talking about that

00:52:06.600 --> 00:52:09.180
makes it so attractive?

00:52:09.180 --> 00:52:18.120
Is it everybody's last
opportunity somehow?

00:52:18.120 --> 00:52:21.600
It's the last
construction of cities

00:52:21.600 --> 00:52:27.030
that made sense to people,
that you knew where you were,

00:52:27.030 --> 00:52:30.030
that it had an enormous
degree of relatability,

00:52:30.030 --> 00:52:32.670
much like Manhattan.

00:52:32.670 --> 00:52:36.510
Manhattan's plan is
as naive, perhaps,

00:52:36.510 --> 00:52:40.140
as linking a bunch of
nodal points with streets.

00:52:43.440 --> 00:52:44.850
Any thought about that?

00:52:47.380 --> 00:52:51.010
Finn Geipel's plan
in the computation

00:52:51.010 --> 00:52:54.820
is an MIT kind of plan.

00:52:54.820 --> 00:52:59.410
He was, three years,
a visiting professor

00:52:59.410 --> 00:53:01.750
before the competition.

00:53:01.750 --> 00:53:10.660
It's a kind of eco-friendly
city with no particular form,

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:14.170
high degrees of--

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:17.980
there's low visibility, but
high degrees of communication

00:53:17.980 --> 00:53:20.800
through telephones,
through all kinds

00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:24.250
of modern electronic
conveniences.

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:31.180
What am I saying?

00:53:31.180 --> 00:53:34.130
Am I arguing that we have
lost a formula for doing

00:53:34.130 --> 00:53:36.530
things which have impact?

00:53:36.530 --> 00:53:40.145
All we do is build taller
buildings with funnier shapes.

00:53:46.605 --> 00:53:49.280
STUDENT: This doesn't
answer your question,

00:53:49.280 --> 00:53:54.572
but it's something that
I'm needing to go back to.

00:53:54.572 --> 00:53:56.780
When Haussmann, and you were
talking about that being

00:53:56.780 --> 00:54:00.650
in the DNA of Paris, the idea,
on things I've always thought

00:54:00.650 --> 00:54:05.150
about Haussmann that never seems
to get talked about as much is

00:54:05.150 --> 00:54:10.130
the relationship of those
streets to the medieval streets

00:54:10.130 --> 00:54:10.890
and how it's--

00:54:10.890 --> 00:54:12.756
I mean that's like the
big difference or one

00:54:12.756 --> 00:54:14.631
of the differences
between how the city works

00:54:14.631 --> 00:54:17.155
and how Haussmann's
intervention in Cairos works

00:54:17.155 --> 00:54:22.640
is Haussmann's streets work in
a context of the preexisting

00:54:22.640 --> 00:54:25.340
streets, versus just
laying those down

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:29.710
and that being your whole
strategy for having a city.

00:54:29.710 --> 00:54:30.585
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

00:54:33.360 --> 00:54:37.380
You'll see, on some of
the slides, some plans

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:44.670
of the Haussmann roads impacting
the existing medieval texture.

00:54:44.670 --> 00:54:46.670
It's pretty ruthless.

00:54:46.670 --> 00:54:50.490
I mean, you know, there's no--

00:54:50.490 --> 00:54:51.240
STUDENT: But the--

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:54.900
JULIAN BEINART:
--notion that the people

00:54:54.900 --> 00:55:00.720
who live under the system,
there's no replacement.

00:55:00.720 --> 00:55:07.560
They pay a marginal penalty
for acquiring the land,

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:08.505
but there's no--

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:16.320
urban renewal, in this country,
produced no great evocative

00:55:16.320 --> 00:55:17.500
features either.

00:55:20.880 --> 00:55:23.580
My point-- it's
rather a nasty point--

00:55:23.580 --> 00:55:26.490
is that if you're
going to be brutal,

00:55:26.490 --> 00:55:28.680
at least produce
something worthwhile.

00:55:28.680 --> 00:55:30.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:30.540 --> 00:55:36.030
If you're going to be
nasty, do it to some effect.

00:55:36.030 --> 00:55:40.110
It's a horrible
principle in modern life

00:55:40.110 --> 00:55:45.780
where we are inclined
to not give power.

00:55:45.780 --> 00:55:52.290
I mean, Haussmann
construed the rules

00:55:52.290 --> 00:55:55.950
so that it was possible
for the Prefect

00:55:55.950 --> 00:56:00.180
of the Seine, the chief
management officer of the city,

00:56:00.180 --> 00:56:05.220
to decide which property
could be confiscated.

00:56:05.220 --> 00:56:09.150
There was no such ruling ever
in England, and certainly not

00:56:09.150 --> 00:56:13.380
in the United States,
under urban renewal.

00:56:13.380 --> 00:56:17.730
But I'm trying to make
the argument that we

00:56:17.730 --> 00:56:20.310
are in a different time.

00:56:20.310 --> 00:56:24.190
We have different
commodities to work with.

00:56:24.190 --> 00:56:25.680
But there's a sense that--

00:56:30.460 --> 00:56:31.690
I know.

00:56:31.690 --> 00:56:35.050
I mean, the critique of
Haussmann's plan by architects

00:56:35.050 --> 00:56:41.140
has been fairly general and
quite right in many respects.

00:56:41.140 --> 00:56:45.790
Richard [INAUDIBLE] argument
against the subdivision

00:56:45.790 --> 00:56:49.390
of the Arondissement
by Haussmann

00:56:49.390 --> 00:56:56.110
in the political units and the
Banlieues being left alone,

00:56:56.110 --> 00:56:57.070
yeah.

00:56:57.070 --> 00:57:04.270
I mean, perhaps I'm talking
about a lost nostalgia

00:57:04.270 --> 00:57:10.720
for a lost unity which
we've now dispatched

00:57:10.720 --> 00:57:14.950
in favor of a greater sense of
well-being about all people.

