01:05:25.950 --> 01:05:32.010
Haussmann and the
dark black being

01:05:32.010 --> 01:05:39.500
the elements that he inserted
into the revised system.

01:05:39.500 --> 01:05:40.000
Next.

01:05:44.090 --> 01:05:46.760
Here, you get the details of a--

01:05:46.760 --> 01:05:48.550
this the Boulevard Sebastopol.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:58.800
That space is taken up at will.

01:05:58.800 --> 01:06:04.660
This connector, it
doesn't matter that there

01:06:04.660 --> 01:06:06.590
are houses underneath here.

01:06:06.590 --> 01:06:11.510
The houses are just separated
away from the others

01:06:11.510 --> 01:06:14.940
in order to make
a new imposition.

01:06:14.940 --> 01:06:18.200
This is about as ruthless as--

01:06:18.200 --> 01:06:24.440
and it's probably the
last time in history

01:06:24.440 --> 01:06:28.200
that this is being able to be
done in a democratic society.

01:06:31.655 --> 01:06:32.155
Next.

01:06:36.680 --> 01:06:41.410
Napoleon didn't pay
much attention to Paris.

01:06:41.410 --> 01:06:44.410
He wanted to make Paris
into a royal city.

01:06:44.410 --> 01:06:49.660
And the East-West access through
the Champs-Élysées became his

01:06:49.660 --> 01:06:55.660
primary focus, the Arc de
Triomphe being the connector--

01:06:55.660 --> 01:07:01.900
not the connector--
being his great monument.

01:07:01.900 --> 01:07:06.640
He also attempted to stretch
the Champs-Élysées eastward

01:07:06.640 --> 01:07:08.410
to the Bastille.

01:07:08.410 --> 01:07:12.520
It's an extraordinary
Haussmannian device.

01:07:12.520 --> 01:07:15.130
This is the Avenue
Fourche, which

01:07:15.130 --> 01:07:19.900
has the wealthiest real
estate in Europe on the sides.

01:07:19.900 --> 01:07:23.710
This street is
about 450 feet wide.

01:07:23.710 --> 01:07:28.150
That's about twice as wide
as Commonwealth Avenue.

01:07:28.150 --> 01:07:31.540
And the Bois-- leading
to the Bois de Boulogne,

01:07:31.540 --> 01:07:35.110
another one of
Haussmann's creations.

01:07:35.110 --> 01:07:37.420
Here's the river.

01:07:37.420 --> 01:07:41.200
Here's the intersection of the
Champs-Élysées into the Bois du

01:07:41.200 --> 01:07:43.415
Boulogne and the Avenue Fourche.

01:07:43.415 --> 01:07:43.915
Next.

01:07:55.378 --> 01:08:04.020
The Académie Nationale de
Musique and the access to it,

01:08:04.020 --> 01:08:09.540
the monument at the end of the
wide road, Avenue de l'Opera.

01:08:09.540 --> 01:08:12.030
Next.

01:08:12.030 --> 01:08:19.229
The interior of the opera by
Garnier, an extraordinary--

01:08:19.229 --> 01:08:24.149
Walter Benjamin writes
about Paris and talks

01:08:24.149 --> 01:08:29.250
about the invention of the
interior, the first time

01:08:29.250 --> 01:08:32.189
that the interior
seen as significant.

01:08:32.189 --> 01:08:37.500
And this study is done by the
students of Foucault, showing

01:08:37.500 --> 01:08:39.960
the subdivision of
the French house

01:08:39.960 --> 01:08:45.240
over time, introducing
what Benjamin calls

01:08:45.240 --> 01:08:49.750
the adventure of the interior.

01:08:49.750 --> 01:08:50.250
Next.

01:08:55.189 --> 01:08:58.700
Here is the ultimate.

01:08:58.700 --> 01:09:03.290
There's the Boulevard
Richard-Lenoir,

01:09:03.290 --> 01:09:09.830
the ultimate expression of
destination and movement

01:09:09.830 --> 01:09:12.200
and the interior connections.

01:09:12.200 --> 01:09:13.580
Next.

01:09:13.580 --> 01:09:16.950
The underground services
in the mid '90s,

01:09:16.950 --> 01:09:20.540
the cross-section
of a Paris street.

01:09:20.540 --> 01:09:24.695
And during one of the
exhibitions in Paris,

01:09:24.695 --> 01:09:30.810
a trip through the sewage
system was a great pleasure.

01:09:33.800 --> 01:09:34.300
Next.

01:09:37.010 --> 01:09:41.960
The Banlieues, here is the
taking down of the dues,

01:09:41.960 --> 01:09:45.930
tax houses on the--

01:09:45.930 --> 01:09:50.569
where the octroi was
collected and the conditions

01:09:50.569 --> 01:09:52.199
in the Banelieues.

01:09:52.199 --> 01:09:52.699
Next.

01:09:55.640 --> 01:09:56.990
In the street is war.

01:09:56.990 --> 01:10:02.140
1848, the barricaded
streets in the center of--

01:10:02.140 --> 01:10:03.110
on the east of--

01:10:07.130 --> 01:10:11.030
on the east of Paris, here
are the barricade lines.

01:10:16.200 --> 01:10:19.440
The use of this street is war.

01:10:23.210 --> 01:10:25.930
Next.

01:10:25.930 --> 01:10:29.620
1872, and the
two-month-long occupation

01:10:29.620 --> 01:10:34.720
of the Western of the
Eastern part of Paris,

01:10:34.720 --> 01:10:37.750
again, with the
use of barricades.

01:10:37.750 --> 01:10:40.990
Barricades slow down
troops, and people

01:10:40.990 --> 01:10:45.940
in the adjacent buildings
can fire down on the troops

01:10:45.940 --> 01:10:47.440
when they slow down.

01:10:47.440 --> 01:10:49.850
Next.

01:10:49.850 --> 01:10:58.515
1968, and again the use
of this street in protest.

01:10:58.515 --> 01:10:59.015
Next.

